<HEADLINE>
FT  27 AUG 92 / London Stock Exchange: Equity futures and options trading
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER PRICE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
TRADING IN the futures market was again dominated by worries over sterling
and the possibility of an increase in UK interest rates, writes Christopher
Price.
The September FT-SE 100 contract opened steadier at 2,293 as dealers and
investors reflected on the chancellors' early morning speech. A small
squeeze sent the contract forward and it reached a high for the day of 2,305
by 9am. It continued to hold up as sterling steadied, but a story that one
German city had reported a rise in its monthly inflation sent September
retreating to 2,280 by midday.
Pressure on sterling, weak gilts and renewed gloom over the UK economy
combined to weaken September throughout the afternoon session, the contract
crumbling to 2,275, its low of the day, by 3pm. However, a firmer Wall
Street helped inspire a rally towards the end. September finished at 2,292,
up 7 from the previous close and around a four-point premium to its fair
value of 5.5. Volume came to 11,580 contracts.
There was again hefty trading in the options market, with the FT-SE 100
option having 10,146 lots dealt out of a total of 34,378. Asda was the
busiest stock option on 7,506 contracts transacted.
