<HEADLINE>
FT  27 AUG 92 / Foreign Exchanges: Modest recovery for sterling
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JAMES BLITZ
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
STERLING recouped  3/4 pfennig against the D-Mark yesterday, following the
Bank of England's most aggressive intervention on the foreign exchanges
since 1986, writes James Blitz.
After an extraordinary day of trading on the sterling/ D-Mark cross, the
pound closed at DM2.7950, nearly two pfennigs above its floor against the
D-Mark in the European exchange rate mechanism.
Some dealers estimated that the Bank had bought around Pounds 1bn in
sterling in the morning, more than has been spent in any previous daily
interventions to support the dollar by the world's central banks. But many
believed that the UK authorities still faced the prospect of raising
interest rates.
In the first hours of London trading, the pound was supported by a statement
from the UK chancellor that there would be no devaluation. Aggressive
intervention followed.
The pound rose above the DM2.7900 level, but fell sharply after a Bundesbank
council member said a realignment of the ERM was possible. The statement was
successfully countered by the UK chancellor and European government
officials. But sterling's gyrations illustrated the currency market's
nervousness.
Can sterling weather the crisis? Mr Julian Simmonds, head of foreign
exchange trading at Citibank in London, thinks it can. 'When sterling hits
its floor, the Bank will be supported by the Bundesbank and other central
banks coming in to buy it,' he said. He also believes that the slowdown in
the German economy should soon bring lower interest rates.
Another respected forex dealer said an interest rate rise, or even
devaluation, was quite possible. 'Politically, a devaluation is not much
more difficult for the UK than a rate rise,' he added. 'I have a feeling
that it is being considered. I cannot otherwise explain why rates have not
yet been raised and intervention is coming so late.'
Mr Jim O'Neill, head of research at Swiss Bank Corp in London, believes the
pound is suffering from a fundamental restructuring of currency portfolios
by pension funds. 'A few institutions are now hedging themselves against the
possibility that there will be a realignment,' he said.
The dollar held its ground against the German currency in spite of a larger
than expected fall in US durable goods orders of 3.4 per cent. It lost
nearly  1/2 pfennig in early US trading on the news but closed at DM1.4065
in London, up 65 basis points on the day. In New York the dollar finally
stood at DM1.4067.
But Mr O'Neill said central banks had missed a good opportunity to rally the
dollar through intervention after the Swiss franc had lost ground in the
morning. 'Intervention would have bid the dollar up,' he said, 'but it never
came.'
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
