<HEADLINE>
FT  27 AUG 92 / International Company News: ABB profits decline 7% in
opening six months
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By IAN RODGER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   ZURICH
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
ABB Asea Brown Boveri, the Swedish-Swiss power engineering group, said
consolidated pre-tax profit in the first half fell 7 per cent to Dollars
496m but forecast that the pre-tax result for the year would reach 'about
last year's level' of Dollars 1.05bn.
'To date, ABB has not experienced any upturn in demand in the recessionary
markets and no improvement in demand is expected in the second half of this
year in the industrialised countries,' the group said.
However, ABB has continued to take in large orders at a rapid pace, notably
from developing countries for power generation plants. In the first half,
the value of new orders totalled Dollars 17.1bn, 18 per cent higher than in
the first half of last year and bringing the group's order backlog at June
30 to Dollars 30.3bn.
However, total revenues grew only 2 per cent to Dollars 13.8bn as the demand
for standard products for industry and construction as well as capital goods
stagnated or turned weaker. Revenues from western European countries were
flat at Dollars 8.1bn and down 13 per cent in North America to Dollars
2.3bn.
Earnings from the power plant division rose while those from environmental
control products and systems declined. The group said earnings from the
other business segments changed only slightly, indicating that margins had
been preserved.
In North America, gains from restructuring were more than offset by lower
sales volumes and prices. Earnings were down in the Nordic region. Earnings
in Germany, Italy, Switzerland and most Asian countries improved.
BBC Brown Boveri, the Swiss group which holds 50 per cent of ABB, said its
consolidated pre-tax profit for the half-year after deduction of third party
interests was SFr344m (Dollars 277.4m), 7.5 per cent lower than in the
comparative period. Revenues were up 5.7 per cent to SFr19.9bn. The board is
proposing to split the bearer and registered shares five for one and to
convert the participation certificates into bearer shares. The latter will
dilute present shareholders' voting power.
</TEXT>
