<BYLINE>
   By SIMON DAVIES
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
WHARF (Holdings), the flagship listing of the empire founded by the late Sir
Yue-kong Pao, announced a HKDollars 900.8m (USDollars 116m) net profit for
the first half of 1992.
The company has changed its year-end from March, and the results represent a
12 per cent increase on the six months to September 1991.
The company also signed letters of intent yesterday for a Yn10bn (USDollars
1.83bn) infrastructure project which will transform the city of Wuhan in the
industrial heartland of China. It includes a containerisation terminal, air
cargo retransportation centre, modernised and expanded rail links and power
supply, and substantial property development.
Wharf's interim results held few surprises. Increased earnings came
primarily from a 10 per cent boost in rental income from its Harbour City
development, and container terminal operator Modern Terminals also showed
strong growth.
But 1992 will be a year of consolidation for the group, before a substantial
increase in the size of its property portfolio comes through in 1993.
Wharf is operating a property rental portfolio of 7m square feet. Within two
years, this will more than double, with the Times Square and Gateway Towers
developments in Hong Kong and Lane Crawford Place in Singapore due to be
completed by the end of 1994.
There was an extraordinary profit of HKDollars 57m from the sale of
long-term investments. The directors recommended an interim dividend of 16.5
cents, up from 14.5 cents in 1991.
