FT  27 AUG 92 / International Company News: PWA boosted by Airbus sale
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT GIBBENS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
PWA, the parent of Canadian Airlines International, is to receive a CDollars
150m (USDollars 126m) cash injection from the sale of its three remaining
Airbus 310 aircraft to the federal government.
PWA will use CDollars 100m to repay debt on the five-year-old aircraft and
CDollars 50m to bolster working capital. The money will give the airlines
breathing space while it tries to negotiate an alliance with American
Airlines or other deals to ensure its survival.
The company has turned down a share exchange offer from Air Canada and is
negotiating an equity injection worth nearly CDollars 200m from all its
employees.
It says it is still negotiating the sale of CDollars 45m of spares for the
Airbus aircraft, made idle by the recession last autumn.
In July, PWA asked Ottawa and three provinces for loan guarantees, saying it
had been driven near to bankruptcy by heavy industry over-capacity and fare
wars with Air Canada. Ottawa then said it might buy the Airbus aircraft on
certain conditions, including merger talks with Air Canada. These talks
failed earlier this month.
Ottawa will use the 310s to replace Boeing 707s now operated by the Armed
Forces.
