<HEADLINE>
FT  27 AUG 92 / UK Company News: Buoyant retail side behind WH Smith rise
27% to Pounds 113m
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MAGGIE URRY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
SIR SIMON Hornby, chairman of WH Smith Group, said he was not expecting any
cyclical recovery in the company's retail markets in the current financial
year.
However, he said the pace of benefits from Smith's pursuit of scale
economies and systems was increasing.
Sir Simon was reporting on results for the year to end-May which showed a 27
per cent jump in pre-tax profits to Pounds 112.7m.
Despite the recession, the group's retail chains - which sell newspapers,
books, stationery, recorded music and videos - increased sales by 10.8 per
cent to Pounds 1.3bn, while sales of its distribution activities - news,
office supplies and books - rose 8.1 per cent to Pounds 905.9m.
Sales in its DIY joint venture fell from Pounds 214.2m to Pounds 209.8m.
Sir Simon said the group had increased market share in virtually all its
retail businesses.
He said the recent reference to the Monopolies and Mergers Commission of the
newspaper distribution industry would not cover magazines, which was the
growth area of the market. Smith's magazine sales rose 10 per cent in the
year.
The MMC would look at the relationship between newspaper publishers and
wholesalers for the first time.
Although the office supplies market was down 9 per cent Smith's sales were
up 10 per cent.
Sir Simon said this business would become 'a major cash producer' and had
won 67 new accounts worth Pounds 12m a year. A new distribution centre was
being built.
A rights issue last year and sales of peripheral businesses had prompted a
Pounds 146.7m fall in net borrowings to Pounds 85.2m - 20 per cent of
shareholders' funds of Pounds 435.4m, up Pounds 185.6m. Interest charges
were down from Pounds 28.2m to Pounds 3.4m.
Profits also benefited from a Pounds 9.2m pension credit. However, this was
down from Pounds 11.2m the year before and Mr John Napier, finance director,
said the credit could be expected to dwindle over the next few years.
Sir Simon said that capital expenditure of Pounds 67m had been financed from
internal resources and spending of Pounds 65m in the current year would be
too.
See Lex
</TEXT>
