<HEADLINE>
FT  27 AUG 92 / Review of building contracts proposed
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW TAYLOR, Construction Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE GOVERNMENT has proposed an independent review of contract arrangements
in the construction industry after complaints that late payments and other
contract abuses are forcing many companies out of business.
The review would also examine customers' complaints that many contractors
bid low prices to win contracts and then try to boost margins by claiming
additional payments during construction.
A letter to industry leaders from the construction policy directorate of the
Department of the Environment says there is profound dissatisfaction with
existing arrangements.
It proposes an independent review of contractual arrangements, jointly
commissioned by government and the industry. The review, which would cover
public and private sector construction contracts, would be expected to
report next autumn. It would cost about Pounds 250,000 and would be financed
jointly.
The proposal follows complaints that many small and medium-sized
sub-contractors have got into difficulties because main contractors have
delayed payments.
The British Constructional Steelwork Association says more than 100 of its
members and their subsidiaries have ceased trading since 1989. It says main
contractors have been boosting their cashflows by withholding payments to
sub-contractors, in some cases for several years.
The association identifies three main areas of contract abuse:
Late repayment of retention money, held back by developers and main
contractors as insurance against defects emerging after work was completed.
Delays in certifying that work has been completed correctly which would
enable bills to be paid promptly.
Querying bills in the knowledge that sub-contractors will accept a lower
payment rather than risk long delays and potentially high legal costs
pursuing extra money.
Money retained against potential defects, normally worth between 2 per cent
and 5 per cent of the contract value, should be repaid a year after legal
completion of work, according to the association. 'One of our members had to
wait five years for repayment because of a dispute over what constituted
legal completion,' it said.
The Environment Department said yesterday that there was deep concern about
the adversarial nature of contract relationships in the construction
industry. The review would be the first commissioned by the government since
the publication 30 years ago of the Branwell Report into construction
contract practices.
Building orders fall by a fifth, Page 7
</TEXT>
