<HEADLINE>
FT  27 AUG 92 / Letter: Jobs follow education in Europe
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   From Mr GILES CATTERMOLE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Sir, Your article on shift work in Europe ('Cost constraints prompt a
continental shift', August 25) did not tell the full story. LSI Logic's
choice of Germany was wrong from the start: 21-shift working is abnormal
there and shift premiums high. In France and the UK, continuous working is
accepted. And in the UK, 21-shift premiums are lower.
There are limits. In France shift workers may not work overtime. In the UK,
union pressure has meant a move from four shift teams for continuous working
to five or six - bearable costs in capital-intensive industries.
So LSI could have found European locations to rival the US, if not Asia. It
probably excluded the UK for lacking a 'highly skilled workforce'.
Giles Cattermole,
chief executive,
Strategy Resource Partners,
8 Hinde Street,
London W1M 5RG
</TEXT>
