FT  27 AUG 92 / Owner-occupation is backed in home surveys
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID BARCHARD
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE PRIVATE rented sector is unlikely to become as significant in the UK
housing market in the foreseeable future as it is in Germany, France or
Scandinavia, according to Housing Finance, the economics journal of the
Council of Mortgage Lenders.
The council says that private rented accommodation makes up only 7.4 per
cent of the UK housing stock, compared with 45 per cent in Germany, 33 per
cent in the US and 18 per cent in France.
Recent market research indicates that owner-occupation was still the most
desired form of tenure in the UK.
The council adds that the surveys show that only a 2 per cent annual
increase in house prices was needed to make ownership more financially
attractive than renting.
