<HEADLINE>
FT  27 AUG 92 / Building orders fall by a fifth
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW TAYLOR, Construction Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
CONSTRUCTION orders won by British contractors slumped by almost a fifth
during the three months to the end of June, according to figures published
yesterday by the Department of the Environment.
The fall in orders, along with fears that British interest rates may have to
rise to defend sterling, sent construction and building material shares
tumbling further on the London stock exchange yesterday.
According to the department the value of construction orders at constant
1985 prices fell by 18 per cent on the corresponding period last year and by
19 per cent compared with the previous three months.
Mr Jack Straw, shadow environment secretary, said: 'These are desperate,
dire figures which show that the recession is still deepening in housing and
construction. They underline the slump in industrial investment.'
He added: 'The slump in this industry is acting as a massive drag on the
rest of the economy.'
Housing and construction activity affected a range of industrial products
from bricks, cement and steel to carpets, textiles, light bulbs and white
goods, said Mr Straw.
According to the environment department, private housing orders in the
second quarter of this year were 13 per cent lower than in the corresponding
period last year and 2 per cent lower than in the previous three months.
Private commercial orders, mainly offices and shops, were 28 per cent lower
than in the corresponding period last year and 29 per cent lower than in the
preceding three months.
Private industrial orders were 28 per cent and 25 per cent respectively
lower over the same periods. Public-sector orders, other than housing, were
8 per cent and 7 per cent lower.
Construction companies have recently expressed concern that the government
may seek to restrain public spending on construction to offset rises in
social security payments caused by rises in unemployment. Contractors, in
particular, fear that road spending could be curtailed.
The only bright spot in the figures was a sharp rise in public housing and
housing association orders which rose by 36 per cent compared with the
corresponding quarter last year.
</TEXT>
