FT  27 AUG 92 / Ford set to cut prices on old stock
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KEVIN DONE, Motor Industry Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
FORD, leader in the UK market for new cars, is expected shortly to announce
price cuts of between Pounds 200 and Pounds 1,000 for selected cars across
its range to dispose of outstanding stocks of 1992 models.
The package of price cuts and other financial incentives is the latest sign
of distress marketing by carmakers in the UK.
The industry has been hit by disappointing sales during the crucial month of
August. Figures released earlier this week showed that registrations in the
first 20 days of the month at 290,550 were only 0.9 per cent higher than the
same period a year ago.
Sales of new cars have not rallied in spite of measures by carmakers
including widespread dealer discounting and offers of free insurance, free
road-fund licences and low-cost finance for buyers.
Ford's last price-cutting initiative came in the wake of the March Budget,
which halved the rate of special car tax from 10 per cent to 5 per cent. In
addition, Ford made further price cuts averaging 3.5 per cent to 4 per cent
on models representing around 30 per cent of its sales volume.
A tentative improvement in overall sales of new cars was achieved in the
three months from April to June, but sales fell year-on-year in July and
after the first seven months of the year registrations were still 4.3 per
cent lower than last year's very depressed level.
Ford and Rover have already imposed short-time working on several of their
UK vehicle assembly lines to cut production and reduce excessive stock
levels.
The indication that Ford is planning another round of price cuts on old
stock follows the warning earlier this week from the Society of Motor
Manufacturers and Traders that rapidly rising imports coupled with the poor
state of domestic demand 'must increase the risk of stock problems in the
months to come'.
</TEXT>
