<HEADLINE>
FT  27 AUG 92 / Exodus of Names from Lloyd's slows
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT PESTON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
NAMES ARE leaving Lloyd's of London at a far slower rate than expected,
according to a senior member of the insurance market's governing council.
About 1,600 Names, the individuals who provide capital to underwrite
insurance risks, are expected to leave at the end of this year, compared
with almost 4,000 who resigned in 1991. That would leave Lloyd's with just
over 20,000 Names next year.
Members of the governing council are becoming increasingly optimistic about
the market's prospects as they await the outcome of a poll of Names, which
is in effect a vote of confidence in the council.
Voting ends at noon on Friday and the result should be known that afternoon.
Names are voting on several resolutions, including a proposal from a
dissident group to rescind the levy imposed in June to top up Lloyd's
central fund, which aims at ensuring that the insurance liabilities of
bankrupt Names are met. It would be an embarrassment to the council if Names
voted to rescind the levy.
However, the senior council member said that such a vote would have a
symbolic effect only as it is impossible for the Pounds 500m raised with the
levy to be returned. 'It could, however, prevent us from making further such
levies.'
Meanwhile, it emerged that the exodus of Names would lead to a reduction in
the market's underwriting capacity from Pounds 10bn to Pounds 9bn. But
Lloyd's has taken some special measures to boost the amount of business that
an individual can underwrite for a given stock of capital to offset the
affect of the Names' resignations. The effect of these measures could be to
maintain the market's underwriting capacity at Pounds 10bn.
The council is also pleased that the average underwriting capacity for each
Name is rising, from Pounds 340,000 in 1988 to Pounds 455,000 this year and
an estimated Pounds 500,000 next year. It believes this shows that only
individuals with the appropriate financial resources are continuing to
participate in the market.
The council also believes that the market's productivity is improving. Its
ratio of overheads to income appears to have risen because of costs
associated with redundancies, but it is convinced that underlying running
costs are falling.
One reason for this is a reduction in the number of syndicates, which pool
Names resources. Smaller syndicates are being absorbed by larger ones,
leading to economies of scale.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
