<HEADLINE>
FT  27 AUG 92 / Plea to lenders on repossessions
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN WILLMAN, Public Policy Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
FEWER PEOPLE might be made homeless if local authorities were informed when
mortgage lenders planned to repossess homes in their area, according to a
report published today by the London Research Centre, an independent think
tank.
A survey of English councils found that nine out of 10 councils rarely or
never received advance notification of repossessions. The Council of
Mortgage Lenders' code of guidance advises lenders to give advance warning
where rehousing by the local authority might be necessary.
The survey found that local authorities had limited scope to help owners in
arrears, apart from delaying repossession until alternative accommodation
could be found.
Few councils operate mortgage-rescue schemes: just 22 had schemes although a
further 25 were planning them. The survey estimates that, among the 19
authorities able to provide figures, only 136 repossessions were halted by
mortgage-rescue schemes in 1991-92. No local authority planned more than 30
rescues for 1992-93.
However, four out of five councils provided some sort of specialist advice
or debt counselling for mortgage arrears, either directly or by funding
agencies such as local Citizens' Advice Bureaux.
And with lenders adopting a more flexible attitude to repossessions, the
report suggests that local authorities may be able to help people with
mortgage arrears to reach arrangements that allow them to remain in their
homes.
Tackling mortgage default: the local authority role. London Research Centre,
81 Black Prince Road, London SE1 7SZ. Pounds 15.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 7
