<HEADLINE>
FT  27 AUG 92 / Exports surge by 50% at British Nuclear Fuels
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NEIL BUCKLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A 50 PER CENT surge in export sales helped British Nuclear Fuels, the
state-owned company that supplies and reprocesses fuel for the nuclear power
industry, increase its annual pre-tax profit by Pounds 5m to Pounds 161m.
Turnover increased by Pounds 40m to Pounds 1,028m, although the rise in
export sales to Pounds 268m was partly offset by what BNFL said was a
temporary reduction in UK sales. The company increased its dividend to the
government, its sole shareholder, by Pounds 2m to Pounds 52m.
Mr Neville Chamberlain, chief executive, said increased exports were the key
to future growth. BNFL had opened an office in Seoul in response to South
Korea's expanding nuclear programme, and it could also have a valuable role
in Russia in improving nuclear safety and by dismantling nuclear weapons.
Two-thirds of BNFL's business is covered by fixed-price deals with Nuclear
Electric and Scottish Nuclear, worth Pounds 17bn over the next 15 years.
Mr Chamberlain said: 'Our future income is largely secured. Whether we
prosper or not depends on how well we control our costs.'
The company's cost-cutting programme has already involved 750 job losses at
its head office at Risley, Cheshire. In May it announced that 550 jobs were
to be lost at its uranium enrichment plant in Capenhurst, Cheshire, because
of the collapse of the market since the end of the cold war.
In addition to providing fuel for other nuclear plants, BNFL operates two
power stations at Calder Hall on the Sellafield site in Cumbria, and
Chapelcross in southern Scotland.
Its Pounds 2.8bn thermal oxide reprocessing plant at Sellafield is due to
open early next year and already has an order book worth about Pounds 9bn.
Sir Christopher Harding, former company chairman, said: 'Those who see
global warming, exacerbated by the burning of fossil fuels, as one of the
main long-term threats to the environment cannot long ignore the benign
contribution to rising world energy demand which nuclear power represents.'
</TEXT>
