FT  27 AUG 92 / Durable goods orders fall
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NANCY DUNNE
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   WASHINGTON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
NEW orders for manufactured durable goods, a key indicator of the US
economy's health, fell 3.4 per cent last month, the US Commerce Department
reported yesterday, Nancy Dunne writes in Washington. The fall, the biggest
since December, was mainly due to a big drop in demand for transport
equipment, especially aircraft, after a revised rise of 2.8 per cent for
June, previously estimated at 2.7 per cent.
The one strength in the new figures was a 2.7 per cent increase in
electronic and electrical equipment orders, with a 3.9 per cent rise in
shipments. The 10 domestic US automakers reported that, despite a 31 per
cent surge in truck sales, car sales had dipped 0.2 per cent for the month.
