<HEADLINE>
FT  27 AUG 92 / Shevardnadze retracts threat of attack: President sees no
progress in efforts to end his army's battle with Abkhazian separatists
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By STEVE LEVINE
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   TBILISI
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
FIGHTING intensified in Georgia yesterday as President Eduard Shevardnadze
said efforts to end his army's battle with Abkhazian separatists were going
nowhere. However, the Georgian president retracted a threat by his regional
commander to attack the Abkhazian stronghold.
Georgian officials yesterday said about 1,500 separatists and northern
Caucasian volunteers had attacked the town of Gagra, near Russia's southern
border, in the worst fighting so far in the two-week conflict. Both sides
reported minimal casualties among their own forces, but claimed to have
inflicted dozens.
Mr Shevardnadze said he was speaking daily by telephone with the leader of
the uprising, Mr Vladislav Ardzinba, and with Russian President Boris
Yeltsin, whom both sides see as a potential mediator. Yesterday, Mr
Shevardnadze sent an envoy with a Russian parliamentary delegation to Mr
Ardzinba's stronghold of Gudauta. The delegation aims to narrow differences
between the sides prior to planned talks on September 3 between Mr
Shevardnadze and Mr Ardzinba, to be overseen by Mr Yeltsin.
Mr Shevardnadze also backed away from an ultimatum issued on Tuesday by the
Georgian commander in Abkhazia, Colonel Gia Karkarashvili. Col Karkarashvili
made the threat - he said he would attack Gudauta directly if Mr Ardzinba
did not surrender by 1pm yesterday - after the Abkhazians killed two
Georgian negotiators during talks on Monday.
'Ultimatums do not work practically,' Mr Shevardnadze said. 'The
commander-in-chief of the guards reacted this way because two of his men
were killed. The only part of the ultimatum that I approved was that if they
stopped blowing up bridges and railways, if they stopped all this, 'we would
no longer be facing you'.'
Mr Shevardnadze made it clear that he accepted a major role for Mr Yeltsin
in ending the conflict. He said Mr Yeltsin had promised to try to seal up
the mountain gorge of Bzipi, through which more than 1,500 forces from
sympathetic northern Caucasians regions, such as Chechenia, have joined the
Abkhazian side.
</TEXT>
