<HEADLINE>
FT  27 AUG 92 / GRE warns on bonuses and quits 'with-profits' sector
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN AUTHERS and ROLAND RUDD
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
GUARDIAN Royal Exchange, the insurance company, said yesterday it would stop
selling 'with-profits' policies. The move intensifies speculation that
investors in with-profits pensions and endowment policies - which support
the majority of British mortgages - will face heavy cuts in the pay-outs
they receive.
Mr James Morley, GRE's finance director, said it was possible that some
insurers' current with-profits policies would not be able to pay the bonuses
needed to cover mortgages.
He added: 'Membership of the (European) ERM means low inflation and low
returns from equities. Paying out bonuses requires a high rate of return. If
you are getting a low rate of return from your assets you have a mismatch
which can only be addressed by reducing bonus rates.'
GRE said the days of the traditional with-profits policy were numbered. Such
policies now accounted for less than 30 per cent of its new business.
It will now follow several other companies, including Standard Life,
Scottish Amicable and Sun Life by offering only unit-linked and unitised
with-profits policies, which put less strain on reserves in the early years
of a policy, because bonuses only need to be added to premiums already paid,
and not to a notional, much larger 'sum assured'.
GRE said: 'We believe that the returns that are being declared by other
companies simply cannot be sustained. They may well be buying their way into
the various league tables of endowment performance. The historical returns
we got in the 1980s cannot be maintained in the 1990s.'
GRE itself cut both its reversionary bonus, paid annually, and its terminal
bonus, paid only when a contract matures, at the beginning of this year.
This badly affected its competitive position compared with other life
offices. It finished bottom in this year's survey of pay-outs for 10-year
policies by Money Management magazine, generally accepted as the industry
standard.
GRE's views on future bonuses were echoed by independent actuaries. Mr
Charles Cannon, actuary with Mercer Fraser, said: 'Looking at the last five
years it is clear that the bonuses being paid out by some companies are
greater than could have been earned by the funds over those five years.' He
said bonuses could not be supported from reserves forever, and predicted
that pay-outs would be cut.
Mr Nick Dumbreck, actuary with R. Watson, agreed. He said: 'There's no doubt
that the with-profits life offices are feeling the pinch this year. We've
seen a number of offices switching out of equities and into fixed interest,
not necessarily because they believe fixed interest is going to perform
better, but because they need it to maintain cover for their solvency
margins.'
Lex, Page 16
Results, Page 17
</TEXT>
