<HEADLINE>
FT  27 AUG 92 / Intervention steadies pound: Bank of England spends Pounds
1bn to hold the line on interest rates
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JAMES BLITZ, PETER MARSH and DAVID MARSH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE BANK of England's biggest intervention to support sterling in six years
helped yesterday to steady the pound against the D-Mark and to stave off a
possible rise in UK interest rates.
The Bank spent about Pounds 1bn buying sterling for D-Marks after Mr Norman
Lamont, the chancellor, stressed that Britain would not devalue the pound or
withdraw from the exchange rate mechanism of the European Monetary System.
The impact of Britain's intervention was reduced after remarks by a member
of the Bundesbank council about the 'potential' for an ERM realignment. The
pound sagged for a few hours before closing in London up  3/4 pfennig at
DM2.7950, 1 1/2 pfennigs above its effective floor in the ERM. In New York,
it was quoted at DM2.7925 at the close and early today was trading at
DM2.7945 as markets opened in Japan.
Mr Lamont, speaking yesterday morning on the steps of the Treasury building
in Whitehall, said he wanted to remove any 'scintilla of doubt' that
government policy was committed to maintaining sterling's ERM position. The
government would do 'whatever necessary' to keep sterling within ERM
parities.
The chancellor's statement was followed by heavy buying of pounds by Bank
currency dealers. In a well-rehearsed operation, they sought to amplify the
effect of Mr Lamont's comments by large purchases of sterling in selected
international banks.
This move was seen on the currency markets as a significant stepping up in
the government's battle to defend the pound. The last time that the Bank
intervened on such a scale to support sterling was in 1986.
But comments yesterday by Mr Reimut Jochimsen, president of the central bank
of North Rhine-Westphalia, strengthened the belief of foreign exchange
dealers that the Bundesbank might be trying to provoke a realignment.
Such a move, which would consolidate Germany's anti-inflation strategy,
might lead to large selling of weaker ERM currencies, including the pound
and the lira.
Mr Jochimsen's remarks were contained in the advance text of a speech he
made yesterday in Dusseldorf. Later in the day, he excised the passage from
his talk. This allowed the Bundesbank to issue a statement denying that it
was seeking a realignment.
Mr Jochimsen's comments fitted in with the views of a growing number of
international economists that the recent strains in financial markets and on
currencies might make a realignment inevitable. Such a move would revalue
upwards strong ERM currencies and depress the value of weak ones.
Yesterday's slight weakening of the D-Mark against the dollar eased
anxieties about the immediate prospect of strains within the ERM pushing up
interest rates across Europe.
The dollar closed in London up some  3/4 pfennig at DM1.4065. Against
sterling, it was nearly half a cent firmer at Dollars 1.9870. In New York it
finished at DM1.4067 and Dollars 1.9845, while early today it was quoted at
DM1.40825 and Dollars 1.98335 shortly after Japanese markets opened.
The faltering signs of dollar strength led to steadier trading on most
European bourses. In London, the FT-SE 100 index of leading shares closed up
4.0 at 2,285.0, helped by a firmer tone on Wall Street, which finished 14.59
higher at 3,246.81.
The rate for three-month money in the sterling cash market eased slightly,
indicating slightly reduced expectations of an imminent rise in bank base
rates, now at 10 per cent. Dealers, however, continued to price in an
increase of at least  3/4 point.
The more settled market conditions led to a reasonably smooth auction by the
Bank of England of Pounds 2.5bn of long-dated gilts. The offer was 1.2 times
subscribed. Gilts, however, closed about  1/2 a point lower in volatile
trading.
Nervousness about sterling's longer-term prospects was heightened by another
opinion poll in France indicating a narrow margin favouring a 'No' vote in
next month's Maastricht referendum.
