FT  26 AUG 92 / International Company News: GM to sell Allison division to
German unit
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MARTIN DICKSON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
GENERAL Motors announced yesterday that it is to sell its Allison
Transmission division to ZF Friedrichshafen, the large German manufacturer
of transmission, steering and suspension products.
GM announced last January that it was putting Indianapolis-based Allison up
for sale as part of a plan to concentrate on its core car and truck
manufacturing operations.
No price was disclosed for the deal, but Allison had 1991 sales of around
Dollars 850m. The subsidiary, employing around 5,000 people, makes automatic
transmissions for trucks, buses, off-highway and military vehicles.
GM said it would continue to rely on the company as a supplier of
transmissions.
Dr Klaus Bleyer, chief executive of ZF, said the deal promoted 'ZF's
long-term strategy of providing world-class powertrain products to a global
customer base'.
The German company, which had 1991 revenues of about Dollars 3.8bn and
already has a substantial manufacturing presence in the US, said it would
maintain Allison's current management and workforce and would continue to
manufacture in Indianapolis.
