<HEADLINE>
FT  26 AUG 92 / International Company News: TWA and pilots agree terms over
restructuring
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KAREN ZAGOR
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
TRANS World Airlines, the debt-laden carrier operating under Chapter 11 of
the US bankruptcy code, yesterday took a significant step towards emerging
from bankruptcy through an agreement in principle with the Air Line Pilots
Association (ALPA).
ALPA, the last union to accept TWA's reorganisation plan, said pilots had
agreed to reduce the costs of wages and benefits by 15 per cent, with
offsets, for three years.
The union said it had received 'contractual language to transfer pilots'
jobs in the event of asset sales, to set requirements for addressing TWA's
pension shortfall, and to ensure appropriate changes to operational
structure'.
Mr Bill Compton, chairman of TWA pilots union, said his executive hoped the
restructuring would lead to a rebirth of TWA. 'With agreements involving the
flight attendants and machinists recently accomplished, our agreement will,
upon ratification, complete TWA's needed cost reductions and enable labour
and the creditors to assist in implementing the required improvements to
TWA's revenue-generating capacity.'
The company's creditors committee, which has agreed to the stand-alone
reorganisation, will forgive about Dollars 1bn of the carrier's roughly
Dollars 1.5bn in debt in exchange for a 55 per cent equity stake in TWA.
</TEXT>
