<HEADLINE>
FT  26 AUG 92 / HSBC surprises with 51% advance
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By SIMON HOLBERTON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   HONG KONG
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
HSBC Holdings, the owner of Hongkong and Shanghai Bank and Midland of the
UK, yesterday surprised analysts when it unveiled a 51 per cent increase in
profits to HKDollars 5bn (Pounds 325m) from HKDollars 3.3bn in the six
months to June 30.
The results, which did not include Midland's interim profit of Pounds 89m or
the bank's recent HKDollars 3.39bn sale of 10 per cent of Cathay Pacific,
were struck after a 63 per cent increase to HKDollars 4.48bn in charges for
bad and doubtful debts.
Olympia &amp; York, the troubled Canadian property company was the main source
of bad debts. At the interim stage, the bank has loans totalling USDollars
768m outstanding to O&amp;Y and made a specific provision of USDollars 187.5m
against them.
A dividend of 70.5 HK cents (4.8p) was declared, 31 per cent up on the 54 HK
cents paid a year ago. It said that shareholders could expect to receive not
less than HKDollars 2 a share in dividends for the whole year, or 14.2p a
share. The bank said it intended to distribute a third of its dividend at
the interim stage and two-thirds at year-end.
Mr William Purves, chairman, said at a press conference late yesterday that
the merger with Midland was proceeding well. 'The things we want to do
should be completed by 1993', he said.
The main operating subsidiary, Hongkong Bank, made a net profit of HKDollars
4bn. This figure includes the bank's share of Hang Seng Bank's profits,
Wardley, its Asia-Pacific merchant banking arm, and Hongkong Bank of
Australia. Although there is no precise comparison with last year, due to
restructuring, the whole of HSBC made HKDollars 3.3bn last time.
Profits in Canada were flat, due to higher provisions, but the British Bank
of the Middle East enjoyed 'strong profit growth', while Australia returned
to profit, and Marine Midland Bank of the US made a half-year profit of
HKDollars 337m compared with a loss last time of HKDollars 849m.
HSBC's costs as a percentage of operating income were 51.6 per cent, and
would have been 60 per cent had Midland's results been incorporated. Mr
Purves said the maintenance of a cost-income ratio of 60 per cent was an aim
of the merged bank.
