FT  26 AUG 92 / Arts: Today's Television
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANTONY THORNCROFT
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Eldorado (BBC 1, 7.00) already seems to have been running forever, getting
through plot lines with the profligacy of a Sun King. If, like me, you have
wondered why so many Brits are clustered together on the Costa del Sol,
there is hard evidence in Coast of Dreams (Channel 4, 9.00) which follows
some real ex-pats who have forsaken the UK for a living in Spain.
Among them is Mike, once a joiner in Southend, who now works 16-hour shifts
preparing 200 roast beef dinners for British tourists. This is the real face
of Eldorado.
It is 23 years since the Rolling Stones' totally spaced-out guitarist Brian
Jones was drowned, and Mick Jagger mourned him by wearing a dress and
reciting Shelley's Adonais in front of the thousands in Hyde Park. Film of
the event features in Mojo Working (Channel 4, 11.15).
Earlier on BBC2 and Radio 3 at 7.30, the oldest orchestra in Russia, the St
Petersburg Philharmonic, plays romantic music at the Proms - Berlioz,
Sibelius and Tchaikovsky.
In Business (Radio 4 at 8.45) examines the impact of the recession on three
companies and asks 'experts' how long the agony will continue.
