FT  26 AUG 92 / Tec chief warns on cuts to budgets
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LISA WOOD, Labour Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE QUALITY of training for school-leavers and unemployed adults may have to
be sacrificed and some of the smallest Training and Enterprise Councils
could close if there are further cuts to their budgets, a senior Tec
representative warned yesterday.
The forecast was the strongest public statement yet from Mr Edward Roberts,
chairman of G10, the group of 10 Tec chairmen who represent to the
government the concerns of Tecs, the employer-led bodies which administer
training schemes in England and Wales.
Earlier this summer Mrs Gillian Shephard, employment secretary, warned Tecs
that their budgets for training could be cut in this year's public
expenditure survey.
Tecs then warned the government privately of the possible adverse effects of
cuts to their training budgets, which last year were cut in real terms. G10
has recently been getting feedback from the other Tec chairmen, who have
been in initial consultations over their spending priorities with the
Department of Employment.
Many chairmen have said that even the maintenance of funding at current
levels will not enable Tecs to meet the growing demand for training
programmes for young people and rising numbers of unemployed adults.
Tecs fear that if the skills of the unemployed are not improved the UK will
not be in a position to take best advantage of any economic upturn.
Mr Edwards said: 'This is the time for government and industry to invest
further in the single most important national resource, our people.
'Tec boards are not prepared to see the Employment Department budget for
training and enterprise reduced without full consideration of the wider
alternatives.'
</TEXT>
