FT  26 AUG 92 / British science 'in decline': British Association for the
Advancement of Science
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CLIVE COOKSON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
BRITISH science is declining in relation to the rest of the world, it was
agreed at the meeting, Clive Cookson writes.
Mr Robert Jackson, junior minister responsible for science, said there was
'a certain inevitability' about the fall as other countries developed.
He denied there was a brain drain. 'Statistics supplied by the universities
show that at every level there is a net inflow (of scientists) into the UK,'
Mr Jackson said.
Dr David Pegg, head of the Medical Research Council's cryobiology unit -
which studies the biology of organisms below their normal temperature  -
said that after the MRC's halt in its funding a leading member is to
emigrate. Dr Michael Taylor will set up an Institute of Cryomedicine - the
study of medicine in freezing temperatures - in Pittsburgh, in the US.
However, Mr David Pendlebury, of the US Institute for Scientific
Information, said the frequency with which UK research was cited worldwide
showed the long-term decline in the impact of British science might 'be
starting to level off'.
