<HEADLINE>
FT  26 AUG 92 / Malaria defies drugs: British Association for the
Advancement of Science
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JENNIE LYNCH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MALARIA IS becoming resistant to all known drugs, Dr Bridget Ogilvie,
director of Wellcome Trust, warned.
Evidence gathered over 10 years by a team of scientists based in Thailand
and funded by Wellcome Trust demonstrates that anti-malarial drugs are
working less effectively in Thai patients. This is because the malarial
parasites are mutating and becoming resistant to drugs.
The scientists predict that many malarial cases will be untreatable within
five years, leading to millions of deaths. Drug-resistant malaria is already
widespread in Saharan Africa. Even quinine, an anti-malarial used for over
500 years, is failing.
'I am confident these results are correct. They show a progressive and
frightening diminution in the efficacy of the drugs, and it's difficult to
interest drug companies into developing new drugs because the research is so
expensive,' Dr Ogilvie said.
One approach towards developing a therapy was outlined by Dr Adrian Hill, a
Wellcome research fellow based in Oxford, who studies the way nature copes
with malaria.
The body's immune system protects against malaria - cells invaded by
malarial parasites become tagged with digested portions of the parasite
called peptides, labelling them as infected and targeting them for
destruction.
Dr Hill said that it was hoped to have in the next five years a vaccine
based on a specific peptide 'which will give useful, if not complete,
protection'.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
