<HEADLINE>
FT  26 AUG 92 / Lib Dems urge shift on ERM
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALISON SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
AN EARLY move for sterling to the narrow bands of the exchange rate
mechanism, perhaps at a lower central rate than the current level, was
suggested yesterday by the Liberal Democrats as part of a package to relieve
the plight of the pound.
Mr Alan Beith, the party's Treasury spokesman, attacked Labour's stance on
the state of the economy, saying that the basis for the European
co-ordination which it had been calling for would not exist before the
French referendum on Maastricht. He agreed with Mr Peter Shore, a former
Labour cabinet minister, that Labour was really calling for devaluation in
saying that it opposed any rise in interest rates whatever happened to the
pound.
He urged Mr John Major, the prime minister, to take a tougher line with the
Tory backbench MPs who were broadcasting their views that there should be a
cut in interest rates to help the domestic economy. He warned that the
prospects of a rise in interest rates would continue to grow unless Mr Major
found ways of improving confidence in the UK economy, such as selective
intervention to help the construction industry.
Mr Beith said that the criterion for any realignment within the ERM must be
that it would result in greater confidence in sterling. He argued that
although a move for sterling to the narrow bands below the central rate
would appear to be devaluation, provided it were coupled with independence
for the Bank of England on interest rates and a British commitment to
European monetary union it could still lead to enhanced rather than reduced
confidence in sterling.
</TEXT>
