<HEADLINE>
FT  26 AUG 92 / Car imports surge breaks trend
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KEVIN DONE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MOTOR industry exports have begun to falter, while imports are again
climbing rapidly, according to figures released yesterday by the Society of
Motor Manufacturers and Traders, Kevin Done writes.
Export earnings for automotive products stagnated in the second quarter of
this year at Pounds 2.87bn following a 6 per cent year-on-year increase in
the first quarter.
By contrast, the value of imported automotive goods jumped by 18 per cent in
the second quarter to Pounds 3.7bn following a 12 per cent year-on-year
increase in the first three months.
As a result, the overall motor-industry trade deficit in the second quarter
more than tripled to Pounds 834m compared with the corresponding period a
year ago, while the deficit in the first half more than doubled to Pounds
1.37bn.
The rapid deterioration of the motor industry's foreign-trade performance in
1992 reverses the marked improvement of recent years. In the final three
months of 1991 the industry achieved the short-lived breakthrough of
recording a quarterly trade surplus for the first time since the early
1980s.
The value and volume of imports of new cars jumped by 20 per cent in the
second quarter from the same period a year ago, in spite of the absence of
any recovery in UK demand for new vehicles, with the value of car imports
totalling Pounds 1.85bn.
The surge in car imports has coincided with a serious reversal in the trend
of UK exports of new cars in the second quarter, with a 9 per cent fall in
value to Pounds 959m from the same period a year ago. This reversed a 3 per
cent year-on-year rise in the first three months.
The decline in the volume of car exports in the second quarter was even more
acute than the drop in value, with a year-on-year fall of 18 per cent. The
volume of car shipments in the first half at 289,833 was 11 per cent lower
than a year ago.
Figures released by the motor industry yesterday show that Ford, the UK
new-car market leader, gained ground modestly in the first 20 days of
August, the most important sales month for new cars.
Registrations of new Ford cars rose by 2.7 per cent to 68,000, while overall
new-car registrations increased by only 0.9 per cent to 290,550.
Vauxhall, which is in second place, suffered a 2.4 per cent fall in sales to
45,000.
Rover was overtaken by the Peugeot group of France, which includes Citroen,
and has fallen into fourth place with a 3.3 per cent drop in sales volume.
It captured 11.2 per cent of sales of new cars compared with 12.2 per cent
by the Peugeot group.
The Citroen marque has emerged as the star performer with a 31.2 per cent
jump in sales to capture a share of 4.8 per cent.
