<HEADLINE>
FT  26 AUG 92 / Builders complain to OFT over plasterboard prices
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW TAYLOR, Construction Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
BUILDERS have complained to the Office of Fair Trading about increases in
plasterboard prices, alleging possible collusion between suppliers.
Recession-hit companies in London, south-west England and the Yorkshire area
fear that large rises in the cost of such a basic material, due to take
effect at the end of this month, could turn low-priced long-term contracts
into lossmakers.
Reductions in discounts, announced this summer by BPB Industries, the
country's largest supplier, are expected to raise plasterboard prices on
average by about 10 per cent. BPB has a 65 per cent share of the UK market.
Lafarge Coppee of France and Knauf of Germany which, together with BPB,
supply virtually all the plasterboard sold in the UK, are expected to raise
prices by similar amounts.
The three companies were until recently locked in a bitter European price
war.
Mr Dennis Maiden, director-general of the Federation of Master Builders
which represents 20,400 building companies, has asked the OFT to investigate
the latest increases. This follow complaints from members that plasterboard
prices in some areas could rise by between 15 per cent and 20 per cent.
BPB said yesterday that price increases, depending upon previous local
discounts, could range from 7 per cent to 20 per cent but would average
about 10 per cent.
It is the second increase to be announced by one of the big three
manufacturers. At the begining of this year Knauf unveiled a rise in British
prices of about 8 per cent.
Mr John Maxwell, BPB's finance director, yesterday estimated that only about
half of this earlier increase, which had been followed by the other
manufacturers, had stuck.
He said: 'Plasterboard prices had fallen by more than 50 per cent since 1987
as a result of the price war. Prices, even with the latest increases, will
still be more than 40 per cent lower than they were five years ago and 30
per cent lower than in 1990.
'There has been no collusion. If other manufacturers decide to follow our
lead it is because they need to increase margins after years of selling at a
loss or break-even.'
The Federation of Master Builders said that increases would hurt small and
medium-sized companies which would be unable to negotiate as big a discount
as larger groups. It said many companies already were operating on contract
margins which did little more than cover overheads.
The federation said: 'Although the increases have yet to come into effect,
we believe that there may have been a degree of collusion between the three
manufacturers which clearly are going to increase prices in line with each
other.'
The OFT said yesterday that it had received a complaint from the federation
and would monitor the situation.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
