<HEADLINE>
FT  26 AUG 92 / Institute of Directors sees sharp fall in economic
confidence
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL CASSELL, Business Correspondent and DAVID BARCHARD
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
CONFIDENCE IN Britain's economic prospects has plunged in the past two
months, according to the Institute of Directors.
The institute's latest survey of business opinion, published today, shows
that only 13 per cent of company directors are more optimistic about the
economy, against 50 per cent in response to the same question in June. But
the institute says directors tend to be less gloomy about prospects for
their own companies than for the whole economy. A third remain optimistic
about the outlook for their businesses, while the number of companies doing
badly is the lowest for 16 months. According to the 325 directors replying
to the survey, two thirds of companies are doing well - a level that has
been constant for 18 months.
The institute concludes that the pattern reflects a crisis of confidence
much more than of substance. Business volume and orders have remained steady
this month while the upward trend in investment - concentrated on machinery
and equipment - has continued.
The institute says that the main concern among directors is insufficient
demand for products, whereas cashflow had been identified as the biggest
problem earlier in the summer - suggesting that a recovery might then have
been under way.
Mr Peter Morgan, director-general of the institute, said the survey 'shows a
great gulf between, on the one hand, directors' perception of the economy
and their business prospects and, on the other, the actual performance of
their companies.
'What we have at present is stable business performance but at a low level
of economic activity. The situation is fragile and a crisis of confidence
could easily be translated into a real downturn.' The Finance and Leasing
Association yesterday reported a 1 per cent increase during the second
quarter of the year over the first quarter in consumer lending and business
finance, David Barchard writes.
However, the association said the rise in new consumer-sector lending was in
line with the same period of 1991 and did not reflect a return of consumer
confidence.
Total consumer credit loans reached Pounds 16.9bn and total business finance
sector lending Pounds 38.7bn. Motor vehicle finance dropped by 1.3 per cent
to Pounds 11.6bn. New lending to the consumer sector rose by 5 per cent to
Pounds 2.5bn, largely as a result of a 12 per cent rise in unsecured
personal loans and a 9 per cent rise in borrowing on store cards.
IoD Business Opinion Survey, Director Publications, 6-20 Elizabeth Street,
London SW1W 9RB. Pounds 15.
</TEXT>
