<HEADLINE>
FT  26 AUG 92 / Middle classes fuel student rise
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW ADONIS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE large increase in student numbers over the past three decades has been
almost entirely drawn from the middle classes, according to research
published by the National Commission on Education.
A research paper issued by the commission, an independent think tank, shows
that the proportion of students from working-class backgrounds going to
higher education has scarcely shifted since 1963.
The paper's author, Professor AH Halsey, of Nuffield College, Oxford, said:
'This is cold comfort for those who seek the classless society.'
He says that fears in the 1960s that the expansion of higher education -
from 216,000 students in 1963 to more than 1m in 1990 - would mean a
dilution of standards were unfounded. The average A-level achievement of
entrants to higher education rose markedly between 1976 and 1984 and has
fallen only slightly since then.
However, the expansion has affected the lecturer/student ratio, which has
declined from 1:8 in 1970 to 1:11.6 last year.
Prof Halsey concludes that Britain is on the road to an American-style
system, where higher education embraces all post-secondary schooling. But,
'plans for funding the new expansion remain vague'.
Higher Education for All? National Commission on Education, 19 Manor
Gardens, London N7 6JY. Free.
</TEXT>
