<HEADLINE>
FT  26 AUG 92 / Rifts re-open in Mideast peace talks
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROGER MATTHEWS and TONY WALKER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   WASHINGTON, CAIRO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE substantial differences between Arab and Israeli negotiators re-emerged
yesterday, after the first round of talks in Washington on Monday, which had
been marked by what all sides described as a distinct improvement in
atmosphere.
The Jordanian and Syrian delegations said they were particularly encouraged
by Israel's willingness to discuss UN Resolutions 242 and 338 'in all their
aspects'. These two resolutions assert the principle of Israel exchanging
Arab land occupied in the 1967 war in return for a comprehensive peace.
Mr Yitzhak Rabin, Israel's prime minister, and Mr Shimon Peres, foreign
minister, have affirmed Israel's commitment to the resolutions. But Mr Rabin
stressed yesterday that Syria had not been given any document or specific
proposals pledging a withdrawal from the Golan Heights.
His comment appeared to qualify an earlier statement by Mr Peres yesterday
that Israel was ready for territorial compromise on the Golan. However, even
this was rejected out of hand by Syria yesterday, before negotiators began
their second round of talks.
Tishrin, the official Damascus daily newspaper, insisted no compromise was
possible on Resolution 242 and demanded full withdrawal by Israel. 'Peace
cannot be achieved through a deal or a partial settlement. There is no
alternative to real peace which gives the Arabs back their occupied land,'
the newspaper said.
The Syrian team said on Monday that if Israel conceded the principle of a
full withdrawal, all matters could be open to discussion.
During five previous rounds of negotiations, Israel, under the hardline
former government headed by Mr Yitzhak Shamir, would not even discuss
territorial compromise.
Similar differences over the interpretation of 242 will emerge as the
negotiations between Israel and the Palestinians move on to substantive
issues in the next four weeks. Israel has already warned that a Palestinian
self-governing authority in the occupied West Bank and Gaza can have only an
administrative function.
The Palestinians want a full legislative body. The aim of both sides is to
agree the form of an elected Palestinian body to administer the areas from
which the Israeli army will withdraw, pending final talks within three years
on a lasting solution for the occupied areas.
</TEXT>
