<HEADLINE>
FT  26 AUG 92 / NTT share sell-off postponed
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By EMIKO TERAZONO
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   TOKYO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE Japanese government announced yesterday that it would postpone the sale
of a tranche of shares of Nippon Telegraph and Telephone, the former
state-owned telecommunications company, in order to avoid depressing the
Tokyo stock market.
The recent slide in NTT shares, prompted by fears that the additional
tranche would depress the stock price, has helped drag down the market in
the past few weeks. The Tokyo market remains vulnerable, although the Nikkei
average has rebounded from its six-year low reached last week following a
government announcement to support the country's ailing banks.
Mr Tsutomu Hata, the finance minister, said plans to offer the remaining
government-held NTT shares during the two years to March 1994 had been
suspended. 'The negative impact could be large on the market,' he said. The
government, which still owns two thirds of NTT, was forced to postpone
planned sales of 500,000 shares last fiscal year because of a sluggish
market.
The decision means the government, which hoped to use revenue from NTT
shares to help fund public works projects, will need to find other means. Mr
Hata said the Finance Ministry was considering issuing construction bonds to
get funds.
Mr Hata said the share price of NTT, which rose as high as Y3.18m (Pounds
12,800) in 1987 and has rebounded from its record low of Y453,000 (Pounds
1,823) reached earlier this month, was a 'symbol' stock on the Tokyo market,
adding that it was important to remove negative factors depressing its share
price.
