<HEADLINE>
FT  26 AUG 92 / Collor defies demands for resignation: Thousands demonstrate
against president in state capitals across the country
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTINA LAMB
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   RIO DE JANEIRO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
PRESIDENT Fernando Collor of Brazil remained defiant yesterday in the face
of mounting public pressure for his resignation following Monday's damning
congressional report accusing him of involvement in a multi-million-dollar
kickback scheme.
Thousands of students and union militants gathered in the commercial centre
of Rio de Janeiro last night dressed in black and shouting 'Out with
corruption. Out with Collor'. Office workers in surrounding buildings threw
shredded paper out of windows to show their support. Other mass
demonstrations were under way in state capitals across the country.
Students, trade unionists, lawyers, intellectuals and politicians calling
for Mr Collor's resignation took part in earlier protests in Sao Paulo, the
country's largest city where up to 500,000 had gathered, and Belo Horizonte,
the third largest city.
Leading intellectuals have issued a manifesto accusing the president of
'breaching the moral and legal limits of his mandate'. Mr Luis Antonio
Fleury, the influential governor of Sao Paulo, demanded the president's
impeachment.
But Mr Collor summoned his entire cabinet to the presidency last night for
an emergency meeting at which he repeated his determination to stay in
office. Afterwards Mr Celio Borja, law minister, said that all ministers had
signed a declaration affirming they would remain in their posts until the
crisis was over.
The 200-page congressional report broadcast live to the nation on Monday
contained nothing that had not previously surfaced in press reports since
investigations began in May, when Mr Collor's younger brother accused him of
corruption. But the report by a 22-member commission was the first official
confirmation of allegations.
It was unsparing in its criticism, accusing Mr Collor of profiting from a
huge corruption racket by his former close friend and campaign treasurer, Mr
Paulo Cesar Farias, and of 'failing in his constitutional duty to uphold
moral standards'.
Congressional discussion on the report began yesterday afternoon and the
commission will vote today on whether to approve its conclusions. There is
little doubt it will be approved, as 13 members have already confirmed their
backing. This will open the way to impeachment proceedings, for which a
two-thirds majority in Congress is necessary, and a possible criminal
investigation.
Mr Collor continues to insist the report was 'political'. He is expected to
produce a counter-report asserting his innocence and laying all the blame on
Mr Farias.
His aides are also planning legal challenges to the report on the grounds
that the commission had no right to investigate the president. The inquiry
was set up to examine Mr Farias' activities.
Mr Collor spent yesterday closeted with pro-government political leaders in
an attempt to ensure the 168 votes necessary to withstand impeachment
proceedings. Government officials claim they have 209 votes but this may be
jeopardised if the Democratic Social party (PDS) withdraws its 44 votes of
support for the government.
Mr Paulo Maluf, PDS president, has already said he is in favour of
impeachment.
Most politicians are keen to avoid a lengthy impeachment and hope public
protests will force Mr Collor to quit.
The economy remains paralysed with inflation running at 23 per cent a month.
Mr Carlos Langoni, a former central bank governor, said: 'If Collor stays on
now, inflation will rise and there is no way the government will be able to
manage the economic situation.'
Editorial Comment, Page 12
</TEXT>
