<HEADLINE>
FT  26 AUG 92 / London Stock Exchange: Equity Futures And Options Trading
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER PRICE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
BUSY trading in the futures market yesterday was once again dominated by
currency and interest rate concerns, writes Christopher Price.
The September contract on the FT-SE Index opened weakly at 2,306 as
independent traders figured large on the selling side. However, a squeeze
developed and, soon after the opening, September moved forward, reaching the
day's high of 2,314 by 10am.
By this time, however, traders' minds were again focused on sterling, the
dollar and the D-Mark, and the effect on UK base rates. As pressure on the
pound mounted, the market began to slide, accentuated in late-morning
trading by a big sell programme by BZW.
Further events combined to maintain the downward pressure: a weak Wall
Street, a French opinion poll on Maastricht, and a large sell order executed
by US broking house Salomon Brothers. September hit 2,256, its low of the
session, late in the day's trading, but rallied towards the end. It finished
at 2,285, down 31 points from the previous close and around a 5-point
premium to its fair value of 5.5. Turnover was 17,139 lots.
In traded options, volume reached 41,335 contracts, of which 15,957 were in
the FT-SE 100 option.
