<HEADLINE>
FT  25 AUG 92 / Commodities and Agriculture: US and Japanese groups in
Dollars 1.5bn Chilean mine deal
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LESLIE CRAWFORD
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   SANTIAGO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
PHELPS DODGE of the US and Sumitomo Metal Mining of Japan were late
yesterday signing a Dollars 1.5bn contract to develop one of the biggest
mining projects of Chile's recent history: the Candelaria copper and gold
deposit in the Atacama desert.
Mr Douglas Yearley, Phelps Dodge's executive president, and his counterpart,
Mr Akihiko Shinozaki of Sumitomo Metal Mining, were in Santiago yesterday to
sign the foreign investment contract with the government of Chile.
The Candelaria deposit was discovered by Phelps Dodge in 1987, and Sumitomo
has taken a 20 per cent stake in the project. It has proven reserves of 400m
tonnes, with an average ore grade of 1.1 per cent copper and 0.26 grams per
tonne of gold. The reserves are expected to last for 34 years.
Phelps Dodge and Sumitomo plan to invest an initial Dollars 500m to strip
the mine and build a concentrator plant. Candelaria will enter production in
1995 with an output of 400,000 tonnes of copper concentrates (a semi-refined
product containing about 30 per cent copper) and 80,000 ounces of gold a
year.
The foreign investment contract of Dollars 1.5bn is expected to cover the
34-year life of the mine.
Mr Tom Foster, Phelps Dodge's vice-president, said the company was
finalising the financial package for Candelaria. Japanese copper smelters
will be putting up some of the money in exchange for supply contracts on
Candelaria's future production; Japan's Export-Import Bank is arranging
project financing, and Phelps Dodge and Sumitomo will complete the package
with their own capital.
Candelaria is the second major copper mine to be developed by foreign
investors after Escondida, the giant deposit owned by BHP of Australia, RTZ
and a group of Japanese smelters led by Mitsubishi.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
