<HEADLINE>
FT  25 AUG 92 / London Stock Exchange: Base rate fears prompt heavy setback
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By TERRY BYLAND, UK Stock Market Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
UK EQUITIES yesterday suff-ered their biggest daily setback since the failed
Soviet coup a year ago, as renewed falls in the US dollar and sterling
fuelled both global economic worries and fears that UK base rates might have
to be raised to protect the pound.
The FT-SE Index dropped 54.6 points, or 2.3 per cent, as shares in
international dollar earners and domestic interest rate-related UK companies
fell heavily. However, trading volume remained moderate and most of the
damage to share prices reflected marking down operations at the opening of
the market.
The Footsie was 45 points down at the first calculation of the day and
extended the loss to 59.7 after Wall Street opened sharply weaker, to record
a day's low of 2,306.0. The stock market, however, steadied as the pound
rallied after moving dangerously close to its ERM floor and Wall Street also
edged off its early low to show a decline of 13 Dow points in UK hours.
The final reading put the FT-SE Index at 2,311.1, with the day's loss of
54.6 just exceeding daily falls recorded earlier this year, notably the
51.5-point loss chalked up in mid-July when one UK building society raised
mortgage rates.
Seaq volume of 383.7m shares yesterday compared with 436.9m on Friday. On
August 19 last year, the Footsie fell by 80.5 (or 3.1 per cent) as London
reacted to the attempted coup in the former Soviet Union.
The continued recovery in the Tokyo market was ignored in London. A widening
in the UK trade deficit to Pounds 934m in July, hardly encouraging for
sterling, was almost lost in the general rush of bearish factors on the
first day of the new equity trading account.
With the City of London braced for further pressure on the dollar and, via
the foreign exchange cross-rates, the pound, share prices were marked down
by marketmakers who did not wait for sellers to arrive. Both marketmakers
and retail investors were inclined to act in stock index futures rather than
in underlying equities, which were often difficult markets.
London shared in the general setback across European bourses as dollar
weakness took effect. But the downturn in the UK market took in substantial
losses in shares which would suffer immediately if UK base rates have to be
raised to protect sterling's position in the ERM network.
Thus, pharmaceuticals, chemicals, stores and building issues all came in for
severe losses. These groups of stocks have traded somewhat erratically in
recent weeks as currency and interest rate factors have ebbed and flowed,
and share prices have become highly volatile.
Equity strategists could find little reason for confidence until the outlook
for sterling and UK interest rates becomes more clear. An attempt at a
modest rally at midsession was wiped out when a UK trading house implemented
a large sell programme across the range of the market. London-based
securities houses have suffered heavy losses since the pound began its
latest slide last week. Trading books are now severely squeezed.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
